==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infatuate
<hw>In*fat"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?; 135)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>infatuatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>infatuare</ets> to infatuate; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>fatuus</ets> foolish. See
<er>Fatuous</er>.]</ety> <def>Infatuated.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infatuate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Infatuate
<hw>In*fat"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Infatuated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Infatuating</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make foolish; to affect with folly; to weaken the
intellectual powers of, or to deprive of sound judgment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The judgment of God will be very visible in <qex>infatuating</qex>
a people . . . ripe and prepared for destruction.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inspire with a foolish and extravagant passion;
<as>as, to be <ex>infatuated</ex> with gaming</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The people are . . . <qex>infatuated</qex> with the notion.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infatuated</ent>⟦br⟧
